<% content_for :title, "#{@post[:title]} | devopsellence blog" %>

<main class="page page-article">
  <header class="article-header">
    <p class="article-back"><%= link_to "&larr; Blog".html_safe, blog_path %></p>
    <h1><%= @post[:title] %></h1>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <time><%= @post[:date].strftime("%B %-d, %Y") %></time>
      <span><%= @post[:reading_time] %></span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="article-body">

    <p>When we launched devopsellence, every runtime concern flowed through GCP. Desired state lived in Cloud Storage. Secrets lived in Secret Manager. Images lived in Artifact Registry. Signing lived in Cloud KMS. Identity lived in Workload Identity Federation. Five GCP services, deeply integrated, providing properties that are genuinely hard to replicate from scratch.</p>

    <p>That architecture served us well. It still does. But it meant that running devopsellence required a GCP project, even if your servers were on Hetzner, in a homelab, or on bare metal in a closet.</p>

    <p>Today we're shipping standalone mode: a complete runtime backend that replaces every GCP dependency with control-plane-native alternatives. <code>devopsellence deploy</code> now works without a Google Cloud account.</p>

    <h2>What we actually changed</h2>

    <p>The previous architecture had one implicit answer to "where does runtime data live?" &mdash; GCP. The control plane published to GCP services, and agents pulled from GCP services. The control plane was the coordinator; GCP was the substrate.</p>

    <p>We needed to make that substrate pluggable without rewriting the coordination layer. That meant identifying the four runtime concerns that were coupled to GCP and giving each one a backend-neutral interface:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Desired-state store</strong> &mdash; where signed deployment specs are persisted and fetched from</li>
      <li><strong>Secret store</strong> &mdash; where runtime secrets are stored and resolved from</li>
      <li><strong>Registry auth source</strong> &mdash; where image pull and push credentials come from</li>
      <li><strong>Runtime identity</strong> &mdash; how agents authenticate to access runtime resources</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Each concern now has two implementations: the original GCP backend and a new standalone backend. The control plane selects the backend per runtime project, not globally. A single installation can run GCP-backed and standalone environments side by side.</p>

    <h2>The Broker pattern</h2>

    <p>The central abstraction is <code>Runtime::Broker</code>. Previously, GCP-specific service calls were scattered across provisioners, publishers, and secret managers. Now they route through a broker that returns the right client for the runtime project's backend.</p>

    <p>The GCP client wraps the existing Cloud Storage, Secret Manager, KMS, and IAM interactions. The standalone client implements the same interface using the control plane's own database and HTTP endpoints. Callers don't know which backend they're talking to.</p>

    <p>This isn't a theoretical abstraction. The standalone client handles real operations:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Provisioning organization, environment, and node bundles with locally-generated identifiers instead of GCP service accounts and IAM bindings</li>
      <li>Storing secrets as encrypted database columns instead of Secret Manager entries</li>
      <li>Publishing desired state to a database-backed document store instead of GCS</li>
      <li>Issuing registry credentials from organization-level configuration instead of Artifact Registry tokens</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Desired state without Cloud Storage</h2>

    <p>In the GCP path, the control plane publishes a signed desired-state envelope to a GCS bucket and the agent polls that bucket directly. The control plane is not in the delivery path &mdash; GCS handles availability and caching.</p>

    <p>In standalone mode, the control plane <em>is</em> the delivery path. The publisher writes the signed envelope to a <code>standalone_desired_state_documents</code> table, keyed by node and sequence number. The agent fetches it from <code>/api/v1/agent/desired_state</code> using its control-plane bearer token.</p>

    <p>The endpoint supports <code>ETag</code> and <code>If-None-Match</code> for conditional fetching, so the agent's 2-second poll loop doesn't re-download unchanged state. Old documents are pruned after each publish, keeping the current and previous sequence to avoid transient gaps during publish.</p>

    <p>The signed envelope format is identical. The agent still verifies the cryptographic signature, still enforces sequence monotonicity, and still caches last-known-good state for offline recovery. The only difference is the transport: HTTP from the control plane instead of HTTP from GCS.</p>

    <h2>Secrets without Secret Manager</h2>

    <p>GCP Secret Manager provides IAM-scoped access, automatic encryption, key rotation, and audit logging. In standalone mode, we trade those properties for simplicity.</p>

    <p>Secret values are stored as encrypted columns in the control plane database using Active Record Encryption with PBKDF2-derived keys. When the control plane publishes desired state for a standalone environment, secret refs point to control-plane HTTP endpoints instead of <code>gsm://</code> URIs. The agent resolves them with its bearer token.</p>

    <p>The authorization model is explicit: the secrets controller checks that the requesting node belongs to the same environment as the secret. A node in environment A cannot fetch secrets from environment B.</p>

    <p>This is a real trade-off. A database compromise with access to the encryption key exposes secret values. Secret Manager's per-secret IAM policies and Cloud Audit Logs are not replicated. For production workloads where that matters, the GCP backend remains the right choice. For a homelab or development environment, encrypted database storage is practical and sufficient.</p>

    <h2>Registry auth without Artifact Registry</h2>

    <p>The GCP path provisions a per-organization Artifact Registry repository and issues short-lived OAuth tokens for push and pull. In standalone mode, you bring your own registry.</p>

    <p>Organizations configure their registry at the control plane level: host, namespace, username, and password (stored encrypted). The CLI's <code>push-auth</code> endpoint returns these credentials for image pushes. The agent's <code>registry-auth</code> endpoint returns them for image pulls. The same credential flow works with Docker Hub, GitHub Container Registry, or any OCI-compatible registry.</p>

    <p>This means the agent no longer assumes <code>.pkg.dev</code> for image pulls. It checks the image reference, determines whether it matches the organization's configured registry, and requests credentials from the control plane if needed. GCP nodes still use Artifact Registry tokens through the existing path.</p>

    <h2>What the agent sees</h2>

    <p>The agent didn't need a mode flag. Instead, it follows the data:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>If the desired-state URI starts with <code>gs://</code>, fetch from GCS with a Google access token</li>
      <li>If it starts with <code>https://</code>, fetch from the control plane with a bearer token</li>
      <li>If a secret ref starts with <code>gsm://</code>, resolve from Secret Manager</li>
      <li>If it's an HTTP URL, resolve from the control plane</li>
      <li>If the image registry isn't <code>.pkg.dev</code>, request credentials from the control plane</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This URI-scheme-driven dispatch means the agent is mixed-fleet safe. A node running a GCP-backed environment and a node running a standalone environment can coexist in the same fleet without a protocol break or flag day.</p>

    <h2>Why this paves the way for AWS</h2>

    <p>Standalone mode is the second implementation of the runtime backend interface. The first was GCP. The third will likely be AWS.</p>

    <p>The mapping is natural:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>S3</strong> for desired state &mdash; same object-storage publish/poll pattern as GCS</li>
      <li><strong>ECR</strong> for images &mdash; same per-org repository model as Artifact Registry</li>
      <li><strong>AWS Secrets Manager</strong> for secrets &mdash; same IAM-scoped access pattern as GSM</li>
      <li><strong>AWS KMS</strong> for signing &mdash; same HSM-backed key operations as Cloud KMS</li>
      <li><strong>IAM Roles Anywhere</strong> for identity &mdash; same certificate-based federation as Workload Identity</li>
    </ul>

    <p>An AWS backend would be a new <code>Runtime::Broker</code> client that implements the same interface as the GCP and standalone clients. The control plane coordination logic, the agent reconciliation loop, the CLI deploy flow, and the signed envelope format all stay the same. The only thing that changes is where runtime data is stored and how agents authenticate to access it.</p>

    <p>Azure, self-hosted MinIO + Vault, and other combinations follow the same pattern. The broker interface is the contract. Each backend implements it using the best primitives available in that environment.</p>

    <h2>The standalone trade-off</h2>

    <p>In standalone mode, the control plane is on the hot path for desired-state fetches, secret resolution, and registry auth. In the GCP path, those operations go directly to GCP services &mdash; the control plane publishes state but isn't involved in delivery.</p>

    <p>This is intentional for v1. Standalone mode is designed for self-hosting, homelabs, and small private installs where simplicity matters more than the resilience properties of a distributed delivery layer. You get the same deploy experience &mdash; <code>devopsellence deploy</code>, zero-downtime rollouts, managed HTTPS, secret injection &mdash; without provisioning any cloud infrastructure.</p>

    <p>If your workload outgrows standalone mode, switching to a cloud-backed runtime is a configuration change on the runtime project. The agent adapts automatically because the backend is encoded in the URIs it receives, not in a compile-time flag.</p>

    <h2>What shipped</h2>

    <p>This is a single branch that touches the control plane, the agent, and the CLI:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Control plane:</strong> runtime broker with standalone client, desired-state document persistence and serving, encrypted secret storage, organization registry config, agent and CLI endpoints for standalone resources</li>
      <li><strong>Agent:</strong> HTTP desired-state fetch with conditional caching, HTTP secret resolution, control-plane registry auth, <code>ControlPlaneAccess</code> for bearer-token-authenticated operations</li>
      <li><strong>CLI:</strong> generic registry push-auth flow that works with any OCI registry</li>
      <li><strong>Tests:</strong> integration coverage for standalone desired state, secrets, registry auth, tunnel tokens, authorization boundaries, and document pruning</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The existing GCP path is unchanged. Every existing test passes. The standalone path is additive &mdash; a new backend option, not a replacement.</p>

    <hr>

